Evaluating Asteroid Characteristics and Predicting Hazard Levels Using NASAâ€™s Asteroid Classification Dataset

2023-10-23

Column Definitions:

1. Neo Reference ID : ID for the Asteroid
2. Name : Name of the Asteroid
3. Absolute Magnitude: It tells about the brightness of the star i.e., Bright star has low magnitude and Dim star has high magnitude
4. Est Dia in KM(min) : This column tells us the estimated minimum size of the asteroid in terms of KM
5. Est Dia in KM(max) : This column tells us the estimated maximum size of the asteroid in terms of KM
6. Close Approach Date : The date when the asteroid was very close to earthâ€™s atmosphere
7. Epoch Date Close Approach : A related date about the asteroidâ€™s close approach
8. Relative Velocity km per sec : The velocity of the asteroid
9. Miss Dist.(Astronomical) : It tells us how far the asteroid came close to Earth, measured in astronomical units
10. Miss Dist.(lunar) : The distance in terms of the Moonâ€™s distance from Earth
11. Miss Dist.(kilometers) : The closest approach of the asteroid to Earth in kilometers
12. Miss Dist.(miles) : The closest approach in miles
13. Orbiting Body : Tells us the orbiting body of the celestial body
14. Orbit ID : An ID for the asteroidâ€™s orbit
15. Orbit Determination Date: The date when the asteroidâ€™s orbit was calculated
16. Orbit Uncertainity Minimum : A measure of the uncertainty in the asteroidâ€™s orbit
17. Orbit Intersection: This column tells about where the asteroidâ€™s orbit crosses
18. Jupiter Tisserand Invariant : The JTI is the planet jupyter force/pull of the celestial bodies surrounding them. The least JTI is on the celestial bodies which is far from the jupiter
19. Epoch Osculation : A specific date related to the asteroid
20. Eccentricity : Decides the shape of the orbit, i.e., 0 < E < 1 : Ellispe, E = 1 : Parabola, E > 1 : Hyperbola
21. Semi Major Axis : It tells us about hoow big the asteroidâ€™s orbit is
22. Inclination : The tilt of the asteroidâ€™s orbit
23. Asc Node Longitude : Where the asteroidâ€™s orbit crosses a reference plane
24. Orbital Period : This column tells us about how long it takes for the asteroid to complete one orbit
25. Perihelion Distance : This column tells us about how close the asteroid gets to the Sun during itâ€™s orbit
26. Perihelion Arg : A measure related to the direction of the asteroidâ€™s orbit
27. Aphelion Dist : This column tells us about how far the asteroid is from the Sun during itâ€™s orbit
28. Perihelion Time : The time when the asteroid is closest to the Sun
29. Mean Anomaly : A measure of where the asteroid is in its orbit
30. Mean Motion : Information about how the asteroid moves in itâ€™s orbit
31. Equinox : The reference point for the orbital information
32. Hazardous: Target variable, tells us if above variables is affecting the asteroid being hazardous to earth. If itâ€™s marked as 1, itâ€™s considered hazardous; if itâ€™s 0, itâ€™s not considered dangerous

Importing Hazardous/Not Asteroid Classification

#To generate the correlation plot between the predictor variables

# Loading the required packages
library(corrplot)
library(dplyr)

# Converting the dataset to a data frame
Ast_Subset <- as.data.frame(Ast_Subset)

# Selecting only the numeric columns from your subset
numeric_columns <- Ast_Subset[, sapply(Ast_Subset, is.numeric)]

# Computing the correlation matrix
correlation_matrix <- cor(numeric_columns)

# Creating a correlation plot
corrplot(correlation_matrix, method = "color", type = "lower", order = "hclust", tl.cex = 0.7)

#To generate feature importance

#Install the following  package (if not already)
#install.packages("randomForest") 

library(randomForest)

# Splitting the dataset into predictors (X) and the target variable (Y)
X <- select(Ast_Subset, -c(Neo.Reference.ID, Name))
Y <- as.factor(Ast_raw$Hazardous)

# Fitting a Random Forest model to determine feature importance
set.seed(123)  # Setting a seed for reproducibility
rf_model <- randomForest(X, Y, ntree = 1000)

# Getting the feature importance
importance <- importance(rf_model)

# Printing importance
print(importance)

** From the above outputs we can infer the following:**

Absolute Magnitude: This feature holds the highest importance score of 104.07, signifying its significant influence on the modelâ€™s capability to differentiate between hazardous and non-hazardous asteroids. In other words, the brightness of the asteroid, represented by its absolute magnitude, plays a crucial role in hazard classification.

Est Dia in KM min and Est Dia in KM max: These two features also possess substantial importance scores, 99.01 and 110.43 respectively. This indicates that the estimated diameter of the asteroid in kilometers is of paramount importance when assessing whether an asteroid is hazardous or not.

Relative Velocity km per sec: While still important, this feature has a comparatively lower importance score of 16.29. It suggests that the asteroidâ€™s velocity, although not as critical as size and magnitude, does contribute to the modelâ€™s ability to make predictions regarding hazard levels.

Orbiting Body: This featureâ€™s importance score is 0.00, implying that it does not impact the modelâ€™s hazard classification. It may be a candidate for removal from the feature set since it has no discernible effect on the predictions.

Orbit Uncertainty: With a moderate importance score of 40.64, this feature contributes to determining hazard levels. It suggests that the degree of uncertainty in an asteroidâ€™s orbit is a relevant factor in classification.

Minimum Orbit Intersection: This feature carries the highest importance score of 469.03, indicating its central role in classifying asteroids as hazardous or not. The closer an asteroidâ€™s orbit intersects with others, the more it influences the hazard classification.

Jupiter Tisserand Invariant, Epoch Osculation, Eccentricity, Semi Major Axis, Inclination, Asc Node Longitude, and Perihelion Distance: These features exhibit varying importance scores. While they may not be as influential as absolute magnitude or asteroid size, they still contribute to the modelâ€™s predictive ability to some extent. These parameters play a role in shaping the modelâ€™s understanding of asteroid hazard.
